---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
    title="LSCSS Principles"
    description="Core principles behind Layered Semantic CSS."
>
    <main class="page-shell">
        <section class="site-hero">
            <p class="eyebrow">Principles</p>

            <h1>
                Core principles
            </h1>

            <p class="intro">
                LSCSS exists to make CSS easier to understand, safer to change,
                and harder to accidentally ruin. Good architecture should reduce
                decisions, not create new ones.
            </p>
        </section>

        <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Principles sections">
            <a href="#why">Why it exists</a>
            <a href="#rules">Core rules</a>
            <a href="#protects">What it protects</a>
            <a href="#next">Where next</a>
        </nav>

        <section id="why" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Why LSCSS exists
            </h2>

            <p>
                Most CSS problems are not caused by missing features. They come
                from unclear ownership, hidden technical debt, unpredictable
                overrides, and systems nobody wants to touch twice.
            </p>

            <p>
                LSCSS is designed to reduce that. It gives teams a predictable
                structure for layers, naming, modifiers, state, utilities,
                theme, legacy code, and temporary fixes.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="rules" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Core rules
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>Organise CSS in explicit cascade layers.</li>
                <li>Keep globally global styles in the base layer.</li>
                <li>Use semantic component names and short child selectors.</li>
                <li>Prefer shallow selectors over deep selector archaeology.</li>
                <li>Keep specificity low and predictable.</li>
                <li>Use modifiers for reusable variants.</li>
                <li>Use <code>.is_*</code> and <code>.has_*</code> for visible state and conditions.</li>
                <li>Keep utilities rare and intentional.</li>
                <li>Theme changes presentation, not structure.</li>
                <li>Legacy CSS stays low. Hacks stay visible.</li>
                <li>Large files trigger review, not pride.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="protects" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                What this protects
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>Layers protect override order.</li>
                <li>Tokens protect consistency.</li>
                <li>Custom media protects breakpoint clarity.</li>
                <li>Scoped selectors protect ownership.</li>
                <li>Modifiers and state protect intent.</li>
                <li>File size guidance protects cognitive load.</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                None of these rules are complicated alone. Together they make
                the system easier to debug and much harder to quietly break.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="next" class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Where next
            </h2>

            <div class="hub-card-grid">
                <article class="hub-card">
                    <h3><a href="/methodology/">Core methodology</a></h3>
                    <p>Learn how layers, naming, architecture, utilities, and theme fit together.</p>
                </article>

                <article class="hub-card">
                    <h3><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></h3>
                    <p>Use practical rules when a CSS decision stops being obvious.</p>
                </article>

                <article class="hub-card">
                    <h3><a href="/playground/">Playground</a></h3>
                    <p>Break components on purpose and learn how to fix them properly.</p>
                </article>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>
</BaseLayout>
